Taxonomic notes: Species from del Hoyo et al. (2014). This species was known as Elegant Imperial-Pigeon, however as the species is only vagrant to Australia, we prefer to follow international conventions of nations to which the species is native.

This taxon has previously been described as a polytypic species - Pied Imperial-Pigeon (Ducula bicolor) which included a Torresian subspecies - Ducula bicolor spilorrhoa (with a core Australian distribution) and a South-east Asian subspecies - Ducula bicolor bicolor among others and the species name applied in Australia until recently was Pied Imperial-Pigeon following following Christides and Boles (2008). However the taxon has more recently been split into separate species with the Australian (Torresian) taxon becoming Ducula spilorrhoa which is now as Torresian Imperial-Pigeon. An additional taxon D. s. constans endemic to the Kimberelys is sometimes also recognised.

[BLI Taxonomic note; Porphyrio porphyrio (Sibley and Monroe 1990, 1993) was split into P. porphyrio, P. indicus, P. madagascariensis, P. melanotus, P. poliocephalus and P. pulverulentus by Sangster et al. (1998), but this treatment is not adopted by the BirdLife Taxonomic Working Group. This is because although there is fair degree of variation between the continental forms of porphyrio (with the race pulverulentus the most distinct), a detailed analysis of character differences is required to determine levels of distinctiveness and variation. Pending such studies, porphyrio is retained as a single polytypic species.]

Treated as polytypic contra Marchant and Higgins (1993), del Hoyo et al. (2014) and Dickenson and Remsen (2013). Treatment based on morphological differences between eastern and western populations (Bennett 2010; Marchant and Higgins 1993), significant ecological differences and demographic isolation across a well known ultrataxon geographic barrier NA the Nullabour coast (Schodde and Mason 1999). Preliminary analysis also suggests significant genetic differentiation between eastern mainland and western mainland populations (Bennett 2010).

Taxonomic notes: Species from del Hoyo et al. (2014). Pezoporus wallicus (Sibley and Monroe 1990, 1993) was split into P. wallicus and P. flaviventris by Murphy et al. (2011), however despite the finding that western flaviventris differs from eastern wallicus+leachi by 4.4 NA 5.1% in mitochondrial DNA (Murphy et al. 2010), the morphological differences are barely detectable, with flaviventris possessing a slightly yellower belly including a reduction to 0 of barring on the lower belly, but we would only score this 1. BLI scoring system does not utilise molecular differences. Pezoporus wallicus is thus listed a polytypic species here and flaviventris a subspecies of wallicus in line with BLI (2012), del Hoyo et al. (2014), Christidis and Boles (2008), Christidis and Boles (1994), Matthews (1912), Clements-Checklists-6.9 but contra North (1911), IOC 5.3 and Murphy et al. (2010).

Recognised as a separate subspecies from the south-eastern population by Mayr (1986), Condon (1951) and Keast (1958) based on plumage differences, but not by Schodde and Mason (1999) who considered that difference may be clinal, but noted their assessment was provisional only due to the very sample of available material for analyses. However, as Christidis et al. (2013) point out, phenotypic distinctions are not likely to be clinal due to the large break in suitable habitat (~250km from a small outlying population on the northern  Eye Peninsula  and nearly 900km from the main central Australian population). Recognised as monotypic species by Dicksinson and Remsen (2013) based on Christidis et al. (2013) who investigated genetic distance measures. BirdLife International/Australia does not utilise genetic only evidence for species delimitation, but we list the taxon as a subspecies here based on the above interpretation pending further phenotypic assessment.

[BLI Taxonomic note; Meliphaga albilineata (Sibley and Monroe 1990, 1993; Christidis and Boles 1994) was split into M. albilineata and M. fordiana by Christidis and Boles (2008) but this treatment is not followed by the BirdLife Taxonomic Working Group (BTWG) because the authors base their treatment on genetic differences between the two taxa but do not quantify what levels of genetic differentiation are acceptable for species level recognition; the BTWG adopts the view of Edwards et al. (2005) that intrageneric genetic differentiation alone is an unsatisfactory basis for species recognition. Furthermore, the BTWG note that Schodde and Mason (1999) describe morphological differences between the two forms as 'fine' and their assertion that there are marked differences in territorial song is undermined by Higgins et al. (2001) who state that further investigation is required; Christidis and Boles (2008) make no reference to vocal differences suggesting that the only basis for this split is molecular evidence.]

[BLI taxonomic note; Heteromyias albispecularis and H. cinereifrons (Sibley and Monroe 1990, 1993) have been lumped into H. albispecularis following Christidis and Boles (1994). H. albispecularis (Christidis and Boles 1994) was again split into H. albispecularis and H. cinereifrons by Christidis and Boles (2008) but this treatment is not followed by the BirdLife Taxonomic Working Group (BTWG) because the authors overturn Schodde & Mason's (1999) rejection of splitting Australian cinereifrons from New Guinean albispecularis simply on the grounds that another group of birds (the Orthonyx logrunners) have the same distributions but have been split because "external similarities were not good indications of conspecificity". This is not sufficient substantiation for a taxonomic change and the BTWG note that morphological differences are slight.]
